Title:     The five don'ts of switch-to-host software development.
             (advice for developers; Comdial's QuickQ and Cintech's
             Prelude automatic call distributors)(Eye on OAI, Column)
Author:    Leibowitz, Ed


Abstract:  Cautionary advice is presented for switch-to-host software
           developers and two switch-to-host automatic call distributors
           (ACD) are described, as well. Software developers should not
           try to implement multiple capabilities all at once, nor should
           they ignore helpful development kits. Developers must keep in
           mind the power capabilities of their hardware and prepare for
           possible application crashes. Systems should not be so
           automated that a company loses touch with its customers.
           Comdial's QuickQ ACD provides visual data on incoming calls in
           real time and can store up to 320 seconds of company
           recordings. It can accommodate up to 64 central office lines
           and 250 agent identifications (ID). Cintech Tele-Management
           Systems' Prelude ACD supports 40 agent IDs and 20 lines and is
           designed for businesses needing basic ACD support. It provides
           incoming call statistics and updates the data in real time.
